    <segment id="1" parent="2" relname="preparation">
Steve Fuller writes:</segment>
    <segment id="2" parent="8" relname="span">

      &quot;STSers are inclined to send out two different messages:

       (1) STSers just want to be left alone to study
          science-in-action...

       (2) STSers want to open up &apos;public understanding of science&apos; to
          include... discussions about the kinds of scientific
          research that should be supported.&quot;
    --------------------------------------------------------------</segment>
    <segment id="3" parent="12" relname="span">

I&apos;m not sure this dichotomy covers all cases. </segment>
    <segment id="4" parent="9" relname="span"> What about a program
for democratizing science by having well-funded research
facilities controlled/staffed by &quot;subaltern&quot; communities
(e.g. lower economic class, people of color), BUT
maintaining the traditional conception of
scientists-choose-their-own-research? </segment>
    <segment id="5" parent="4" relname="elaboration">  That is, not so much
anti-expertism as changing the constitution of
the expert community. </segment>
    <segment id="6" parent="10" relname="disjunction">  Should #2 above be expanded,</segment>
    <segment id="7" parent="10" relname="disjunction"> or should we have
more than two categories?</segment>
